  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Maximum sentences can increase for more serious cases\n\n2. Financial penalties:\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the transaction\n\n3. Asset forfeiture:\n- Government can seize assets connected to laundered funds\n- Property, bank accounts, and other financial instruments may be confiscated\n\n4. Additional consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential immigration consequences for non-citizens\n\nSpecific penalties depend on factors like transaction amount, criminal history, and specific circumstances of the offense. The exact charges are typically prosecuted under 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 and \u00a7 1957.\n\nNote: This is general legal information, not specific legal advice. Actual penalties can vary based on case details and jurisdiction.",
